{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3097cade-4b67-45c3-bc97-3c80885af097","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports (`.ips` files):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for a `.ips` file named after your process. These contain backtraces, register state, and loaded images. You can also find them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n**Core dumps (if needed):**\nCore dumps are off by default. To enable them *before* reproducing:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n```\nCores are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\nFor NativeAOT, the `.ips` crash report is usually sufficient — it includes native frames that map directly to your compiled code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"42ec71fb-66b1-46d1-8310-287b9c5d1ff0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the OS automatically generates a crash report (`.ips` file) in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user processes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system processes). macOS does not produce traditional core dumps by default (they're disabled via `kern.coredump`), but the `.ips` crash logs contain the thread backtraces, register state, and loaded binary images.\n\n\nSince NativeAOT doesn't include `createdump`, the user should look for those `.ips` files in the DiagnosticReports folder, or optionally enable core dumps manually by running `ulimit -c unlimited` and `sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1`, which will write dumps to `/cores/`.","outputTokens":501,"requestId":"A0C3:39E965:948B3A:B6EBFE:6A0136B6"},"id":"152baea0-7f3d-4587-8ebd-745be079f8b7","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:54:09.914Z","parentId":"31bce369-fdd0-4e3b-81d9-39bc3a2cb93e"}
